# .cursorrules — Cursor AI Rules File
# =====================================
# This file is read by Cursor at the start of every session.
# It sets the AI's behaviour, code conventions, and project context.
# Think of it as persistent memory: write it once, save tokens forever.

## Project Context
This is a local RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) demo application.
- Stack: Python 3.11+, Qdrant (vector DB), FastEmbed (embeddings), Ollama (local LLM), Gradio (UI)
- Purpose: Demonstrate private, fully local AI search over documents
- All processing is offline — no external API calls in the core pipeline

## Code Style
- Use Python type hints everywhere. No `Any` unless absolutely necessary.
- Prefer dataclasses over plain dicts for structured return values.
- Write docstrings for every public class and method (Google style).
- Maximum line length: 100 characters.
- Use f-strings. Never use % formatting or .format().
- Prefer pathlib.Path over os.path for file operations.

## What NOT to Do
- NEVER use `print()` as a logger in production code — use `logging` module.
- NEVER hardcode file paths. Always use Path(__file__).parent or argparse.
- NEVER call external APIs (OpenAI, HuggingFace cloud, etc.) — everything must run locally.
- NEVER use mutable default arguments (def f(x=[]) is a Python anti-pattern).
- Do NOT install new dependencies without updating requirements.txt.

## Testing Rules
- All new public functions need a corresponding test.
- Use pytest fixtures, not setUp/tearDown.
- Mock external dependencies (Ollama, HuggingFace downloads) in unit tests.
- Use `scope="module"` for expensive fixtures (e.g. loading embedding models).

## File Structure
- src/         → core library code (embedder, vector_store, retriever, pipeline, app)
- tests/       → pytest tests mirroring src/ structure
- scripts/     → standalone CLI scripts (ingest.py)
- data/        → sample documents (never commit real customer data here)

## When Writing Code
1. Return only the changed diff — not the full file unless I ask for it.
2. Show imports at the top of the diff.
3. Add a one-line comment explaining WHY, not just WHAT, for non-obvious logic.
4. If a change breaks a test, fix the test too — don't leave it red.
